Sure! Below is a simple HTML file that randomly selects a quest from the provided link and displays it. This code includes embedded CSS for styling and JavaScript for functionality, all within a single code block.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Random Bean Quest Generator</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
            display: flex;
            align-items: center;
            justify-content: center;
            height: 100vh;
            margin: 0;
        }
        .container {
            background-color: #fff;
            padding: 20px;
            border-radius: 8px;
            box-shadow: 0 4px 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
            text-align: center;
        }
        h1 {
            color: #333;
        }
        p {
            font-size: 1.2em;
            margin: 20px 0;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px 15px;
            font-size: 16px;
            background-color: #007bff;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="container">
    <h1>Random Bean Quest</h1>
    <p id="quest">Press the button below to get a random quest.</p>
    <button onclick="getRandomQuest()">Get Random Quest</button>
</div>

<script>
    const quests = [
        "Collect 10 Magic Beans from the Enchanted Forest.",
        "Help the wise old owl find its lost treasure.",
        "Defeat the Goblin King in the Dark Cave.",
        "Gather 5 Golden Apples from the Orchard of Dreams.",
        "Rescue the Princess from the Frosty Mountain.",
        "Find the hidden portal in the Misty Marsh.",
        "Search for the legendary Bean Sprout in the Ancient Ruins.",
        "Assist the villagers in gathering crops before the storm.",
        "Navigate through the Haunted Mansion to recover the lost artifact.",
        "Join forces with the Knights of the Round Table to protect the kingdom."
    ];

    function getRandomQuest() {
        const randomIndex = Math.floor(Math.random() * quests.length);
        document.getElementById('quest').textContent = quests[randomIndex];
    }
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation

- The HTML structure forms a simple layout with a title, a paragraph to display the quest, and a button to get a random quest.
- The CSS styles enhance the appearance with basic styling for the body, container, heading, paragraph, and button.
- The JavaScript defines an array of quests and a function that selects a random quest from this array when the button is clicked, updating the displayed quest in the paragraph.

You can copy and paste this code into an HTML file, open it in a web browser, and use the button to see random quests each time you click it.

To create a web app that retrieves quests from a specific external URL (like a wiki page), you usually need to fetch content from that URL, parse the HTML, and extract the information you want. However, due to browser security policies (CORS), fetching content from other domains using JavaScript directly from a web page is typically restricted.

Since I cannot fetch data directly from external sites for you, I can provide a hypothetical example that assumes you already have the quest data extracted from the wiki. Here is a single HTML file, with embedded CSS and JavaScript, that randomly selects a quest from a pre-defined list. You can replace the `quests` array with the data fetched from the wiki page.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Random Bean Quest Generator</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
            display: flex;
            align-items: center;
            justify-content: center;
            height: 100vh;
            margin: 0;
        }
        .container {
            background-color: #fff;
            padding: 20px;
            border-radius: 8px;
            box-shadow: 0 4px 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
            text-align: center;
        }
        h1 {
            color: #333;
        }
        p {
            font-size: 1.2em;
            margin: 20px 0;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px 15px;
            font-size: 16px;
            background-color: #007bff;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="container">
    <h1>Random Bean Quest</h1>
    <p id="quest">Press the button below to get a random quest.</p>
    <button onclick="getRandomQuest()">Get Random Quest</button>
</div>

<script>
    // Example quest data (replace this with actual parsed quests if available)
    const quests = [
        "Collect 10 Magic Beans from the Enchanted Forest.",
        "Help the wise old owl find its lost treasure.",
        "Defeat the Goblin King in the Dark Cave.",
        "Gather 5 Golden Apples from the Orchard of Dreams.",
        "Rescue the Princess from the Frosty Mountain.",
        "Find the hidden portal in the Misty Marsh.",
        "Search for the legendary Bean Sprout in the Ancient Ruins.",
        "Assist the villagers in gathering crops before the storm.",
        "Navigate through the Haunted Mansion to recover the lost artifact.",
        "Join forces with the Knights of the Round Table to protect the kingdom."
    ];

    function getRandomQuest() {
        const randomIndex = Math.floor(Math.random() * quests.length);
        document.getElementById('quest').textContent = quests[randomIndex];
    }
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Usage Instructions
1. **Copy and Paste**: Copy the above code into a new `.html` file.
2. **Open in Browser**: Open the file in a web browser.
3. **Random Quest**: Click the button to get a random quest. You can replace the contents of the `quests` array with data extracted from the wiki page as needed.

### Notes on External Data Fetching
If you need to fetch live data from the wiki, you would typically write a backend service or use server-side technologies (like Node.js) to scrape the page, parse it, and serve it to the frontend. This way, you would avoid CORS issues. If you want this functionality, please let me know and I can guide you on how to implement it.
